4. Configuration Options (exact option names and effects):
- start (integer): inclusive start of sequence. Default 1.
- end (integer): inclusive end of sequence. Default 100.
- rules (ordered list or map of divisor -> token): evaluated in declared order. Default {3: "fizz", 5: "buzz"}.
- digit_rules (boolean or list): when true, treat presence of divisor digit in decimal representation as a match for that divisor. Default false.
- concat_mode (boolean): when true, build tokens by concatenation (Pattern B). When false, use precedence rules (Pattern A). Default depends on implementation but recommend true for extensibility.
- output_mode ("list" | "stream"): whether to return an in-memory collection or a lazy iterator/generator. Default "list".

5. Complexity and Performance
- Time complexity: O(n * r * d) where n is count of numbers, r is number of rules, d is digit-check cost (if digit rules used). Typical r is small (2), so effectively O(n).
- Space complexity: O(n) for list output; O(1) additional for streaming generator.
- Performance tips:
  - Prefer streaming for large end values to avoid memory blow-up.
  - Use concatenation approach to avoid repeated lcm computations when rules increase.
  - Precompute divisibility thresholds where applicable; keep rule evaluation order deterministic.

6. Edge Cases and Testing
- Edge cases to assert in unit tests:
  - start > end -> empty output (or defined behavior). Decide and document.
  - negative numbers and zero: define behavior; zero is divisible by any non-zero divisor, so typically fizzbuzz at zero.
  - very large end values -> ensure streaming to avoid OOM.
  - digit_rules interplay: test e.g., 53 when rules for 5 and digit_rules true.
  - non-integer or null inputs -> validate and throw/raise appropriate error.
- Minimal test vectors (express as assertions rather than code):
  - fizzBuzz(15) includes "fizzbuzz" at position 15.
  - With default rules, positions 3,6,9 -> fizz; 5,10 -> buzz; 15 -> fizzbuzz.

7. Best Practices and Implementation Patterns (concrete):
- Provide a configuration object for rule injection to make the function reusable in tests and interview variations.
- Prefer deterministic, ordered rule evaluation to avoid non-determinism when rules conflict.
- Expose both list and generator APIs so consumers can choose memory vs convenience.
- Use concatenation approach for multi-rule extensibility; it is simpler to reason about and implement.
- Document behavior for zero and negative ranges explicitly in the public API docs.

8. Troubleshooting Checklist (step-by-step):
- Symptom: "FizzBuzz not printing fizzbuzz at 15". Checkpoints:
  1. Verify combined-case check (mod 15) runs before exclusive checks if using precedence approach; or ensure concatenation appends both tokens.
  2. Verify integer arithmetic (no accidental floats). Ensure modulo operation semantics match language.
  3. Confirm start/end indexing: ensure you are mapping index-to-number correctly (off-by-one errors).

- Symptom: "Memory explosion on large N". Checkpoints:
  1. Are you returning an array for very large end? Consider streaming/GPU processing.
  2. Are temporary strings being retained? Use streaming yields to avoid accumulation.

